16 in the unincorporated areas of the county; (2) deposit the money collected from the fee
17 into an enterprise fund; and (3) use the money from the fee to fund an area or zone for
18 the preservation of the endangered or threatened species or subspecies. (NRS 244.386)
19 Existing law also allows the governing body of a city to: (1) impose a similar fee if the
20 county in which the city is located has created such an enterprise fund; (2) deposit the
21 fee into the enterprise fund; and (3) use the money collected from the fee to take certain
22 measures to conserve the endangered or threatened species or subspecies. (NRS
23 268.4413, 268.4415). Sections 3.3, 3.7 and 3.9 of this bill allow the money collected from
24 such fees to also be used for the establishment of plans and programs for the
25 conservation of the habitat and ecosystems in certain areas or zones. Sections 3.3 and 3.7
26 require any such fee collected to be based upon an economic analysis of the cost to carry
27 out such a plan or program for habitat and ecosystem conservation. Section 3.3 also
28 authorizes a board of county commissioners that imposes such a fee to adjust the fee for
29 inflation beginning in Fiscal Year 2026-2027.
30 Existing law requires, subject to certain exceptions, sheriffs, county recorders and county
31 auditors, county clerks, county assessors and county treasurers to keep open the county office
32 and branch offices, if any, on all days except Sundays and nonjudicial days from 9 a.m. to 12
33 p.m., and on all days except Sundays, nonjudicial days and Saturdays from 1 p.m. to 5 p.m.
34 Existing law also authorizes the board of county commissioners of any county to designate or
35 authorize deviation from the days and hours, but requires each office to be kept open for not
36 less than 40 hours during each week. (NRS 245.040) Existing law establishes that the county
37 treasurers are tax receivers for the county. (NRS 361.475) Section 3.5 of this bill provides that
38 the county office and branch offices, if any, of the county treasurer may not close earlier than
39 5 p.m. on any business day but may close later than 5 p.m.
40 Existing law requires the tax receiver of the county to mail notice of delinquent taxes to
41 certain persons. The notice of delinquency must state certain information including that if the
42 amount of delinquent taxes is not paid, the tax receiver will, at 5 p.m. on the first Monday in
43 June of the current year, issue a certificate authorizing the county treasurer to hold the
44 property. (NRS 361.5648) Section 4 of this bill provides instead that the notice of delinquency
45 must state that if the amount of delinquent taxes is not paid, the tax receiver will, at the close
46 of business of the tax receiver of the county on the first Monday in June of the current year,
47 issue a certificate authorizing the county treasurer to hold the property.
48 Existing law requires the tax receiver to make out a trustee’s certificate that describes
49 each property on which delinquent taxes, penalties, interest and costs have not been paid. The
50 trustee’s certificate authorizes the county treasurer to hold each property for a certain period
51 of time. (NRS 361.570) When the time allowed by law for the redemption of a property
52 described in a certificate has expired and no redemption has been made, the tax receiver who
53 issued the certificate is required to execute and deliver to the county treasurer a deed of the
54 property. Upon obtaining such a deed, the county treasurer is required to hold the property in
55 trust until it is sold or otherwise disposed of. Existing law provides that during certain periods
56 or not later than 5 p.m. on the third business day before the day of the sale by a county
57 treasurer, certain persons are entitled to have the property reconveyed upon the receipt by the
58 county treasurer of payment of the delinquent taxes and certain costs. (NRS 361.585) Section
59 5 of this bill provides instead that during certain periods or not later than the close of business
60 of the county treasurer on the third business day before the day of the sale by a county
61 treasurer, certain persons are entitled to have the property reconveyed upon the receipt by the
62 county treasurer of payment of the delinquent taxes and certain costs.
63 Existing law authorizes, under certain circumstances, the county treasurer to sell property
64 held in trust because of delinquent taxes. Upon payment, the county treasurer is required, with
65 certain exceptions, to issue a quitclaim deed to the purchaser. Existing law provides an
66 exception to this requirement to issue a quitclaim deed under certain circumstances, if, not
67 later than 5 p.m. on the third business day immediately preceding the day of the sale by the
68 county treasurer, a municipality provides the county treasurer with an affidavit that meets
69 certain requirements. (NRS 361.595) Section 6 of this bill provides instead that, under certain
70 circumstances, the county treasurer may not issue the quitclaim deed if, not later than the
71 close of business of the county treasurer on the third business day immediately preceding the
72 day of the sale by the county treasurer, a municipality provides the county treasurer with an
73 affidavit that meets certain requirements.

